          <avActivityHighlights>Wind slabs represent the main danger.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>The sometimes strong wind has transported some snow. The large wind slabs can be released even by a single winter sport participant in all aspects above approximately 2000 m. This applies in particular at transitions from a shallow to a deep snowpack, when entering gullies and bowls for example. The current avalanche situation calls for careful route selection. &lt;br/&gt; As a consequence of falling temperatures, the natural activity of moist and wet avalanches will appreciably decrease.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>Over a wide area 100 to 150 cm of snow, and up to 180 cm in some localities, has fallen since Saturday. The moderate wind has transported the new snow significantly. &lt;br/&gt; The new snow has settled to a large extent at low and intermediate altitudes. &lt;br/&gt; Intermediate and high altitudes: Individual weak layers exist in the old snowpack especially on shady slopes. &lt;br/&gt; The surface of the snowpack will soften later than the day before. This applies in particular at low and intermediate altitudes.</snowpackStructureComment>
        </BulletinMeasurements>
      </bulletinResultsOf>
    </Bulletin>
